{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:52:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15244"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15244"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.07,0.02,0.17,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104763"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7935"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"82"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104763"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman has a medical emergency (MET) call overnight for sudden onset palpitations. She had been admitted to hospital that day for investigation of recurrent palpitations and presyncope. She has a past medical history of severe asthma requiring multiple hospital admissions in the past year, and eczema. Her medications include salbutamol, budesonide/formoterol, montelukast, and a topical corticosteroid as required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn arrival of the MET team, she appears anxious but alert. She has no chest pain but feels short of breath. Her pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her heart sounds are rapid but regular and with no murmurs. A 12-lead ECG shows a narrow complex regular tachycardia with no visible P waves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarotid sinus massage is attempted after auscultating the carotids and ensuring no bruit is present. Her rhythm and rate remain unchanged on the cardiac monitor.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous adenosine","Intravenous metoprolol","Defibrillation","Intravenous verapamil","Immediate electrical cardioversion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with likely supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) based on the sudden onset, regular narrow complex tachycardia without visible P waves. While she is currently haemodynamically stable, prompt management is required. However, her severe asthma significantly influences the choice of pharmacological treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVagal manoeuvres have failed, making \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous verapamil\u003C/strong\u003E the most appropriate next step. Verapamil is an effective treatment for SVT and, importantly, is safe to use in patients with asthma. It works by blocking calcium channels in the atrioventricular node, thereby terminating re-entrant tachycardias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous adenosine\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be the first-line pharmacological treatment for stable SVT. However, it is contraindicated in patients with severe asthma as it can precipitate severe bronchospasm through its action on adenosine receptors in the airways. Given this patient\u0027s history of multiple asthma admissions, adenosine should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in patients with severe asthma due to the risk of bronchospasm from beta-receptor blockade. Even cardioselective beta-blockers can precipitate bronchospasm in patients with severe asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate electrical cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient showed signs of shock, severe hypotension, or altered consciousness. This patient is currently stable and conscious, making pharmacological cardioversion more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the delivery of an unsynchronised electrical shock and is used for unstable ventricular tachycardia or ventricular fibrillation. It would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous in SVT, where synchronised cardioversion would be used if electrical therapy was required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of SVT in patients with severe asthma requires careful consideration of drug contraindications. When adenosine and beta-blockers are contraindicated, verapamil becomes an important alternative for pharmacological cardioversion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adenosine is contraindicated in patients with severe asthma due to risk of bronchospasm.","Intravenous verapamil is an alternative treatment for stable supraventricular tachycardia when adenosine is contraindicated.","Beta-blockers should be avoided in patients with severe asthma when treating supraventricular tachycardia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2023 Jun [cited 2025 Jun 4]. Available from: https://app.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Supraventricular Arrhythmias, JACC, 2016; 67(13): e27-115.Page, R, Joglar, J, Caldwell, M. et al. 2015 ACC/AHA/HRS Guideline for the Management of Adult Patients With Supraventricular Tachycardia: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Practice Guidelines and the Heart Rhythm Society. JACC. 2016 Apr, 67 (13) e27\u2013e115. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2015.08.856"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15244"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-04T01:31:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-28T12:38:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7935"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104763"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Manageme